15 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4. (a) Criminal history information for an
16 employee or a former employee may not be introduced as evidence
17 against an employer, an employer's agents, or an employer's employees
18 in a civil action that is based on the conduct of the employee or the
19 former employee if:
20 (1) the nature of the criminal history information of the employee
21 or former employee does not bear a direct relationship to the facts
22 underlying the civil action;
23 (2) before the acts giving rise to the civil action occurred:
24 (A) a court order sealed the record of the criminal case;
25 (B) the criminal conviction has been reversed or vacated;
26 (C) the employee or former employee received a pardon for
27 the criminal conviction; or
28 (D) the criminal conviction has been expunged under
29 IC 35-38-9 (before its repeal) or IC 35-38-9.5; or
30 (3) the criminal history information concerns an arrest or a charge
31 that did not result in a criminal conviction.
32 (b) This section does not supersede any federal or state law
33 requirement to:
34 (1) conduct a criminal history information background
35 investigation; or
36 (2) consider criminal history information in hiring for particular
37 types of employment.
38 SECTION 9. IC 31-39-8.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
39 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
40 JULY 1, 2026]:
41 Chapter 8.5. Expungement of Juvenile Arrest Records
42 Sec. 1. (a) This chapter applies to an expungement petition filed
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

9
1 after June 30, 2026.
2 (b) This section applies only to a child who has been arrested or
3 alleged to be a delinquent child, if:
4 (1) the arrest or juvenile delinquency allegation:
5 (A) did not result in a juvenile adjudication, even if the
6 arrest or juvenile delinquency allegation resulted in an
7 adjudication for an infraction; or
8 (B) resulted in a juvenile adjudication that was expunged
9 or was later vacated; and
10 (2) the child is not currently participating in a pretrial
11 diversion program, unless the prosecuting attorney authorizes
12 the child to petition for an expungement under this section.
13 (c) This subsection applies to a child alleged to be a delinquent
14 child after June 30, 2022. If:
15 (1) a court dismisses all juvenile delinquency allegations;
16 filed and pending against a child;
17 (2) one (1) year has passed since juvenile delinquency
18 allegations were filed against a child, and:
19 (A) there is no disposition or order of waiver; and
20 (B) the state is not actively prosecuting the allegations; or
21 (3) in a juvenile proceeding the court finds all allegations not
22 true, or the juvenile's true finding is later vacated;
23 the court shall immediately order all records related to the juvenile
24 delinquency allegations expunged. An expungement order that is
25 issued based on nonprosecution under subdivision (2) goes into
26 effect immediately. An expungement order issued under
27 subdivision (1) or (3) may not go into effect earlier than sixty (60)
28 days from the date of the dismissal or not true finding. However,
29 upon motion by the prosecuting attorney, if the court finds that
30 specific facts exist in the particular case which justify a delay, the
31 court may delay implementation of an expungement order under
32 subdivision (1) or (3) for up to one (1) year from the date of the
33 dismissal, acquittal, or no true finding.
34 (d) This subsection applies to a child arrested after June 30,
35 2022. If:
36 (1) a child is arrested;
37 (2) one (1) year has elapsed since the date of the arrest; and
38 (3) no delinquency allegations are pending against the child;
39 the child may petition a judge exercising juvenile jurisdiction in the
40 county (or a designated judge, if applicable) for expungement,
41 setting forth these facts. Upon receipt of the petition, the judge
42 shall immediately order the expungement of all records related to
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

10
1 the arrest. Expungement under this subsection does not shorten the
2 statute of limitations. A prosecuting attorney may still file
3 delinquency allegations under this subsection.
4 (e) Not earlier than one (1) year after the date of arrest or
5 juvenile delinquency allegation (whichever is later), if the child was
6 not adjudicated a delinquent child, or the opinion vacating the
7 adjudication becomes final, the child may petition the court for
8 expungement of the records related to the arrest or juvenile
9 delinquency allegation. However, a child may petition the court for
10 expungement at an earlier time if the prosecuting attorney agrees
11 in writing to an earlier time.
12 (f) A petition for expungement of records must be verified and
13 filed in a circuit or superior court in the county where the juvenile
14 delinquency allegations were filed, or if no juvenile delinquency
15 allegations were filed, in the county where the arrest occurred. The
16 petition must set forth:
17 (1) the date of the arrest or juvenile delinquency allegation
18 and true finding (if applicable);
19 (2) the county in which the arrest occurred and the county in
20 which the juvenile delinquency allegations were filed, if
21 applicable;
22 (3) the law enforcement agency employing the arresting
23 officer, if known;
24 (4) the court in which the juvenile delinquency allegations
25 were filed, if applicable;
26 (5) any other known identifying information, such as:
27 (A) the name of the arresting officer;
28 (B) the case number or court cause number;
29 (C) any aliases or other names used by the petitioner;
30 (D) the petitioner's driver's license number; and
31 (E) a list of each delinquency allegation and its disposition,
32 if applicable;
33 (6) the date of the petitioner's birth; and
34 (7) the petitioner's Social Security number.
35 A child who files a petition under this section is not required to pay
36 a filing fee.
37 (g) The court shall serve a copy of the petition for expungement
38 on the prosecuting attorney.
39 (h) Upon receipt of a petition for expungement, the court:
40 (1) may summarily deny the petition if the petition does not
41 meet the requirements of this section, or if the statements
42 contained in the petition indicate that the petitioner is not
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

11
1 entitled to relief; and
2 (2) shall grant the petition unless:
3 (A) the conditions described in subsection (b) have not
4 been met; or
5 (B) delinquency allegations are pending against the child.
6 (i) Whenever the petition of a child under this section is granted,
7 or if an expungement order is issued without a petition under
8 subsection (c):
9 (1) no information concerning the arrest, juvenile delinquency
10 allegation, or vacated juvenile delinquency adjudication
11 (including information from a collateral action that identifies
12 the petitioner), may be placed or retained in any state central
13 repository for criminal history information or in any other
14 alphabetically arranged criminal history information system
15 maintained by a local, regional, or statewide law enforcement
16 agency;
17 (2) the clerk of the supreme court shall seal or redact any
18 records in the clerk's possession that relate to the arrest,
19 juvenile delinquency allegation, or vacated juvenile
20 delinquency adjudication; and
21 (3) the records of:
22 (A) the juvenile court;
23 (B) a court that conducted a collateral action;
24 (C) a court of appeals; and
25 (D) the supreme court;
26 concerning the child shall be redacted or permanently sealed
27 from public access.
28 (j) If the court issues an order granting a petition for
29 expungement under this section, or issues an order for
30 expungement without a petition under subsection (c), the order
31 must include the information described in subsection (f).
32 (k) If a child whose records are expunged brings an action that
33 might be defended with the contents of the expunged records, the
34 defendant is presumed to have a complete defense to the action. In
35 order for the plaintiff to recover, the plaintiff must show that the
36 contents of the expunged records would not exonerate the
37 defendant. The plaintiff may be required to state under oath
38 whether the plaintiff had records in the juvenile justice system and
39 whether those records were expunged. If the plaintiff denies the
40 existence of the records, the defendant may prove their existence
41 in any manner compatible with the law of evidence.
