5 Sec. 15. (a) If the prosecuting attorney does not object, or has
6 waived objection to the petition under section 14 of this chapter,
7 the court may grant the petition for expungement without a
8 hearing.
9 (b) The court may summarily deny a petition, if the petition
10 does not meet the requirements of section 14 of this chapter, or if
11 the statements contained in the petition demonstrate that the
12 petitioner is not entitled to relief.
13 (c) If the prosecuting attorney objects to the petition, the
14 prosecuting attorney shall file the reasons for objecting to the
15 petition with the court and serve a copy of the objections on the
16 petitioner at the time the prosecuting attorney objects to the
17 petition. The court shall set the matter for hearing not sooner than
18 sixty (60) days after service of the petition on the prosecuting
19 attorney.
20 (d) A victim of the offense for which expungement is sought may
21 submit an oral or written statement in support of or in opposition
22 to the petition at the time of the hearing. The petitioner must prove
23 by a preponderance of the evidence that the facts alleged in the
24 verified petition are true.
25 (e) The grant or denial of a petition is an appealable final order.
26 (f) If the court grants the petition for expungement, the court
27 shall issue an order of expungement as described in sections 12 and
28 13 of this chapter.
29 (g) The order granting the petition for expungement described
30 in sections 12 and 13 of this chapter must include the information
31 described in section 14(b) of this chapter.
32 (h) A petitioner may seek to expunge more than one (1)
33 conviction at the same time. The petitioner shall consolidate all
34 convictions that the petitioner wishes to expunge from the same
35 county in one (1) petition. A petitioner who wishes to expunge
36 convictions from separate counties must file a petition in each
37 county in which a conviction was entered.
