7 Sec. 17. (a) This section does not apply to a person to whom
8 sealed records may be disclosed under this chapter. With respect
9 to a person seeking employment with a law enforcement agency or
10 a probation or community corrections department, including
11 volunteer employment, subsections (b), (d), (e), and (f) do not apply
12 to the law enforcement agency or the probation or community
13 corrections department.
14 (b) It is unlawful discrimination for any person to:
15 (1) suspend;
16 (2) expel;
17 (3) refuse to employ;
18 (4) refuse to admit;
19 (5) refuse to grant or renew a license, permit, or certificate
20 necessary to engage in any activity, occupation, or profession;
21 or
22 (6) otherwise discriminate against;
23 any person because of a conviction or arrest record expunged or
24 sealed under this chapter.
25 (c) Except as provided in section 12(g) of this chapter, the civil
26 rights of a person whose conviction has been expunged shall be
27 fully restored, including the right to vote, to hold public office, to
28 be a proper person under IC 35-47-1-7(2), and to serve as a juror.
29 (d) In any application for employment, a license, or other right
30 or privilege, a person may be questioned about a previous criminal
31 record only in terms that exclude expunged convictions or arrests,
32 such as: "Have you ever been arrested for or convicted of a crime
33 that has not been expunged by a court?".
34 (e) A person whose record is expunged shall be treated as if the
35 person had never been convicted of the offense. However, upon a
36 subsequent arrest or conviction for an unrelated offense, the prior
37 expunged conviction:
38 (1) may be considered by the court in determining the
39 sentence imposed for the new offense;
40 (2) is a prior unrelated conviction for purposes of:
41 (A) a habitual offender enhancement; and
42 (B) enhancing the new offense based on a prior conviction;
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

24
1 and
2 (3) may be admitted as evidence in the proceeding for a new
3 offense as if the conviction had not been expunged.
4 (f) Any person that discriminates against a person as described
5 in subsection (b) commits a Class C infraction and may be held in
6 contempt by the court issuing the order of expungement or by any
7 other court of general jurisdiction. Any person may file a written
8 motion of contempt to bring an alleged violation of this section to
9 the attention of a court. In addition, the person is entitled to
10 injunctive relief.
11 (g) In any judicial or administrative proceeding alleging
12 negligence or other fault, an order of expungement may be
13 introduced as evidence of the person's exercise of due care in
14 hiring, retaining, licensing, certifying, admitting to a school or
15 program, or otherwise transacting business or engaging in activity
16 with the person to whom the order of expungement was issued.
17 (h) A conviction, including any records relating to the conviction
18 and any records concerning a collateral action, that has been
19 expunged under this chapter is not admissible as evidence in an
20 action for negligent hiring, admission, or licensure against a person
21 or entity who relied on the order.
22 (i) An expungement case, and all documents filed in the case,
23 becomes confidential when the court issues an expungement order.
24 However, until the court issues an expungement order, documents
