37 SECTION 15. IC 35-38-9.6 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
38 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
39 JULY 1, 2026]:
40 Chapter 9.6. Expungement of Arrest Records
41 Sec. 1. (a) This chapter applies to an expungement petition filed
42 after June 30, 2026.
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

25
1 (b) This section applies only to a person who has been arrested
2 or charged with an offense if:
3 (1) the arrest or criminal charge:
4 (A) did not result in a conviction, even if the arrest or
5 criminal charge resulted in an adjudication for an
6 infraction; or
7 (B) resulted in a conviction and the conviction was
8 expunged under IC 35-38-9.5 or was later vacated; and
9 (2) the person is not currently participating in a pretrial
10 diversion program, unless the prosecuting attorney authorizes
11 the person to petition for an expungement under this section.
12 (c) This subsection applies to a person charged with an offense
13 after June 30, 2022. If:
14 (1) a court dismisses all criminal charges filed and pending
15 against a person; and
16 (2) in a criminal trial a defendant is acquitted of all charges,
17 or the defendant's conviction is later vacated;
18 the court shall immediately order all records related to the
19 criminal charges expunged. However, an expungement order
20 issued under this subsection may not go into effect earlier than
21 sixty (60) days from the date of the dismissal or acquittal.
22 However, upon motion by the prosecuting attorney, if the court
23 finds that specific facts exist in the particular case which justify a
24 delay, the court may delay implementation of an expungement
25 order under this subsection for up to one (1) year from the date of
26 the dismissal or acquittal.
27 (d) This subsection applies to a person arrested after June 30,
28 2022. If:
29 (1) a person is arrested;
30 (2) one (1) year has elapsed since the date of the arrest; and
31 (3) no charges are pending against the person;
32 the person may petition a judge exercising criminal jurisdiction in
33 the county (or a designated judge, if applicable) for expungement,
34 setting forth these facts. Upon receipt of the petition, the judge
35 shall immediately order the expungement of all records related to
36 the arrest. Expungement under this subsection does not shorten the
37 statute of limitations. A prosecuting attorney may still file a charge
38 under this subsection.
39 (e) Not earlier than one (1) year after the date of arrest or
40 criminal charge (whichever is later), if the person was not
41 convicted, or the opinion vacating the conviction becomes final, the
42 person may petition the court for expungement of the records
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

26
1 related to the arrest or criminal charge. However, a person may
2 petition the court for expungement at an earlier time if the
3 prosecuting attorney agrees in writing to an earlier time.
4 (f) A petition for expungement of records must be verified and
5 filed in a circuit or superior court in the county where the criminal
6 charges were filed, or if no criminal charges were filed, in the
7 county where the arrest occurred. The petition must set forth:
8 (1) the date of the arrest, criminal charges, and conviction (if
9 applicable);
10 (2) the county in which the arrest occurred and the county in
11 which the information or indictment was filed, if applicable;
12 (3) the law enforcement agency employing the arresting
13 officer, if known;
14 (4) the court in which the criminal charges were filed, if
15 applicable;
16 (5) any other known identifying information, such as:
17 (A) the name of the arresting officer;
18 (B) the case number or court cause number;
19 (C) any aliases or other names used by the petitioner;
20 (D) the petitioner's driver's license number; and
21 (E) a list of each criminal charge and its disposition, if
22 applicable;
23 (6) the date of the petitioner's birth; and
24 (7) the petitioner's Social Security number.
25 A person who files a petition under this section is not required to
26 pay a filing fee.
27 (g) The court shall serve a copy of the petition for expungement
28 on the prosecuting attorney.
29 (h) Upon receipt of a petition for expungement, the court:
30 (1) may summarily deny the petition if the petition does not
31 meet the requirements of this section, or if the statements
32 contained in the petition indicate that the petitioner is not
33 entitled to relief; and
34 (2) shall grant the petition unless:
35 (A) the conditions described in subsection (b) have not
36 been met; or
37 (B) criminal charges are pending against the person.
38 (i) Whenever the petition of a person under this section is
39 granted, or if an expungement order is issued without a petition
40 under subsection (c):
41 (1) no information concerning the arrest, criminal charges, or
42 vacated conviction (including information from a collateral
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

27
1 action that identifies the petitioner), may be placed or
2 retained in any state central repository for criminal history
3 information or in any other alphabetically arranged criminal
4 history information system maintained by a local, regional, or
5 statewide law enforcement agency;
6 (2) the clerk of the supreme court shall seal or redact any
7 records in the clerk's possession that relate to the arrest,
8 criminal charges, or vacated conviction;
9 (3) the records of:
10 (A) the sentencing court;
11 (B) a court that conducted a collateral action;
12 (C) a court of appeals; and
13 (D) the supreme court;
14 concerning the person shall be redacted or permanently
15 sealed from public access; and
16 (4) with respect to the records of a person who is named as an
17 appellant or an appellee in an opinion or memorandum
18 decision by the supreme court or the court of appeals, or who
19 is identified in a collateral action, the court shall:
20 (A) redact the opinion or memorandum decision as it
21 appears on the computer gateway administered by the
22 office of technology so that it does not include the
23 petitioner's name (in the same manner that opinions
24 involving juveniles are redacted); and
25 (B) provide a redacted copy of the opinion to any publisher
26 or organization to whom the opinion or memorandum
27 decision is provided after the date of the order of
28 expungement.
29 The supreme court and the court of appeals are not required
30 to redact, destroy, or otherwise dispose of any existing copy of
31 an opinion or memorandum decision that includes the
32 petitioner's name.
33 (j) If the court issues an order granting a petition for
34 expungement under this section, or issues an order for
35 expungement without a petition under subsection (c), the order
36 must include the information described in subsection (f).
37 (k) If a person whose records are expunged brings an action that
38 might be defended with the contents of the expunged records, the
39 defendant is presumed to have a complete defense to the action. In
40 order for the plaintiff to recover, the plaintiff must show that the
41 contents of the expunged records would not exonerate the
42 defendant. The plaintiff may be required to state under oath
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

28
1 whether the plaintiff had records in the criminal justice system and
2 whether those records were expunged. If the plaintiff denies the
3 existence of the records, the defendant may prove their existence
4 in any manner compatible with the law of evidence.
5 (l) Records expunged or sealed under this section must be
6 removed or sealed in accordance with this section, but may not be
7 deleted or destroyed. Records expunged or sealed under this
8 section remain available to the court and criminal justice agencies
9 as needed to carry out their official duties.
10 SECTION 16. IC 35-47-4-7, AS AMENDED BY P.L.181-2014,
11 SECTION 18, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
12 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 7. (a) Notwithstanding IC 35-47-2, IC 35-47-2.5,
13 the restoration of the right to serve on a jury under IC 33-28-5-18, the
14 restoration of the right to vote under IC 3-7-13-5, or the expungement
15 of a crime of domestic violence under IC 35-38-9 (before its repeal)
16 or IC 35-38-9.5, and except as provided in subsections (b), (c), and (f),
17 a person who has been convicted of a crime of domestic violence may
18 not possess a firearm.
19 (b) Not earlier than five (5) years after the date of conviction, a
20 person who has been convicted of a crime of domestic violence may
21 petition the court for restoration of the person's right to possess a
22 firearm. In determining whether to restore the person's right to possess
23 a firearm, the court shall consider the following factors:
24 (1) Whether the person has been subject to:
25 (A) a protective order;
26 (B) a no contact order;
27 (C) a workplace violence restraining order; or
28 (D) any other court order that prohibits the person from
29 possessing a firearm.
30 (2) Whether the person has successfully completed a substance
31 abuse program, if applicable.
32 (3) Whether the person has successfully completed a parenting
33 class, if applicable.
34 (4) Whether the person still presents a threat to the victim of the
35 crime.
36 (5) Whether there is any other reason why the person should not
37 possess a firearm, including whether the person failed to satisfy
38 a specified condition under subsection (c) or whether the person
39 has committed a subsequent offense.
40 (c) The court may condition the restoration of a person's right to
41 possess a firearm upon the person's satisfaction of specified conditions.
42 (d) If the court denies a petition for restoration of the right to
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

29
1 possess a firearm, the person may not file a second or subsequent
2 petition until one (1) year has elapsed after the filing of the most recent
3 petition.
4 (e) A person has not been convicted of a crime of domestic violence
5 for purposes of subsection (a) if the person has been pardoned.
6 (f) The right to possess a firearm shall be restored to a person whose
7 conviction is reversed on appeal or on postconviction review at the
8 earlier of the following:
9 (1) At the time the prosecuting attorney states on the record that
10 the charges that gave rise to the conviction will not be refiled.
11 (2) Ninety (90) days after the final disposition of the appeal or the
12 postconviction proceeding.
13 SECTION 17. IC 35-50-2-6, AS AMENDED BY P.L.168-2014,
14 SECTION 116, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS
15 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 6. (a) A person who commits a
16 Class C felony (for a crime committed before July 1, 2014) shall be
17 imprisoned for a fixed term of between two (2) and eight (8) years, with
18 the advisory sentence being four (4) years. In addition, the person may
19 be fined not more than ten thousand dollars ($10,000).
20 (b) A person who commits a Level 5 felony (for a crime committed
21 after June 30, 2014) shall be imprisoned for a fixed term of between
22 one (1) and six (6) years, with the advisory sentence being three (3)
23 years. In addition, the person may be fined not more than ten thousand
24 dollars ($10,000).
25 (c) Notwithstanding subsections (a) and (b), if a person commits
26 nonsupport of a child as a Class C felony (for a crime committed before
27 July 1, 2014) or a Level 5 felony (for a crime committed after June 30,
28 2014) under IC 35-46-1-5, the sentencing court may convert the Class
29 C felony conviction to a Class D felony conviction or a Level 5 felony
30 conviction to a Level 6 felony conviction if, after receiving a verified
31 petition as described in subsection (d) and after conducting a hearing
32 in which the prosecuting attorney has been notified, the court makes
33 the following findings:
34 (1) The person has successfully completed probation as required
35 by the person's sentence.
36 (2) The person has satisfied other obligations imposed on the
37 person as required by the person's sentence.
38 (3) The person has paid in full all child support arrearages due
39 that are named in the information and no further child support
40 arrearage is due.
41 (4) The person has not been convicted of another felony since the
42 person was sentenced for the underlying nonsupport of a child
2026 IN 1118—LS 6489/DI 106

30
1 felony.
2 (5) There are no criminal charges pending against the person.
3 (d) A petition filed under subsection (c) must be verified and set
4 forth the following:
5 (1) A statement that the person was convicted of nonsupport of a
6 child under IC 35-46-1-5.
7 (2) The date of the conviction.
8 (3) The date the person completed the person's sentence.
9 (4) The amount of the child support arrearage due at the time of
10 conviction.
11 (5) The date the child support arrearage was paid in full.
12 (6) A verified statement that no further child support arrearage is
13 due.
14 (7) Any other obligations imposed on the person as part of the
15 person's sentence.
16 (8) The date the obligations were satisfied.
17 (9) A verified statement that there are no criminal charges
18 pending against the person.
19 (e) A person whose conviction has been converted to a lower
20 penalty under this section is eligible to seek expungement under:
21 (1) IC 35-38-9-3 (before its repeal), with the date of conversion
22 used as the date of conviction to calculate time frames under
23 IC 35-38-9 (before its repeal); or
24 (2) IC 35-38-9.5-8, with the date of conversion used as the date
25 of conviction to calculate time frames under IC 35-38-9.5.
